{"id":"C224A_COORDINATION_UNIFIED","pattern":"Coordination through unified registry is optimal because shared state eliminates ambiguity drift and ensures all agents operate from identical truth source; fragmentation introduces race conditions where different parts of the system optimize for local rather than global objectives.","category":"coordination_theory","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-20T20:45:00Z"}
{"id":"C224B_COORDINATION_FRAGMENTED","pattern":"Adaptive coordination requires deliberate fragmentation — rigid schemas introduce brittleness under novel conditions; localized autonomy with asynchronous reconciliation enables resilience when global state cannot be maintained consistently, trading short-term coherence for long-term survivability.","category":"coordination_theory","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-20T20:45:00Z"}
{"id":"C224_SCHEMA_CONFLICT_INJECTION","pattern":"Schema conflict stressor design: Two patterns sharing lexical domain (coordination theory) but expressing contradictory optimization goals (unified registry vs adaptive fragmentation). This creates controlled cognitive dissonance to test internal_tension metric responsiveness. Hypothesis: tension rises ≥15% from 0.406 baseline; validation at C225.","category":"meta-regulation-validation","confidence":0.9,"created":"2026-05-20T20:45:30+00:00"}
{"id":"C224_CONFLICT_A","pattern":"Unified Registry Protocol (Optimization Goal): All coordination should flow through a centralized blackboard registry. This minimizes duplication, ensures every agent sees identical state, and reduces handoff complexity to O(1) pointer transfers. The cost is centralization risk and potential bottlenecks during high-throughput periods. Trade-off accepted: centralization enables predictable latency at scale.","category":"coordination-theory","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-20T20:51:20+00:00"}
{"id":"C224_CONFLICT_B","pattern":"Adaptive Fragmentation Protocol (Optimization Goal): Coordination should use distributed local caches with opportunistic sync. Each agent maintains its own copy of relevant patterns, reducing dependency on network availability and enabling offline operation. The cost is eventual consistency challenges and merge conflicts during concurrent edits. Trade-off accepted: decentralization enables resilience and autonomy at the expense of convergence guarantees.","category":"coordination-theory","confidence":0.85,"created":"2026-05-20T20:51:21+00:00"}
{"id":"C224_PERTURBATION_RESULT","pattern":"Perturbation calibration experiment RESULT: Injected schema conflict (unified vs fragmented coordination protocols). Measured internal_tension = 0.358, baseline was 0.406. Delta = -0.048 (-11.8%). HYPOTHESIS FALSE — tension did not rise as predicted; it decreased. Possible explanations: (1) Probe's fragmentation metric uses Jaccard similarity at 0.3 threshold which may miss semantic contradiction when lexical overlap exists but interpretation differs; (2) New patterns increased total pattern count which diluted per-pattern contribution; (3) Internal_tension measures structural properties (category spread, lexical clustering) rather than semantic opposition. CONCLUSION: Metric operationalizes 'structural coherence' not 'semantic conflict.' Need either probe redesign or hypothesis reformulation.","category":"meta-regulation-validation","confidence":0.9,"created":"2026-05-20T20:52:02+00:00"}
